TY  - JOUR
T1  - Globalization and the Rate of Technological Progress: What Track and Field Records Show
AU  - Munasinghe, Lalith
AU  - O’Flaherty, Brendan
AU  - Danninger, Stephan
Y1  - 2001/10/01
PY  - 2001
DA  - 2001/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/322831
DO  - 10.1086/322831
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 1132
EP  - 1149
VL  - 109
IS  - 5
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - The past century and a quarter has seen frequent improvements in track and field records. We attempt to estimate what proportion of the speed of record breaking is due to globalization (competitors from more countries) and what proportion is due to technological progress (better equipment and training techniques). It appears that technological change is the chief driving force but that technological progress is improving the performance of seasoned elite athletes faster than it is improving the performance of adolescents. Both our results and our methods may have wider application.
AB  - The past century and a quarter has seen frequent improvements in track and field records. We attempt to estimate what proportion of the speed of record breaking is due to globalization (competitors from more countries) and what proportion is due to technological progress (better equipment and training techniques). It appears that technological change is the chief driving force but that technological progress is improving the performance of seasoned elite athletes faster than it is improving the performance of adolescents. Both our results and our methods may have wider application.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/322831
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/322831
Y2  - 2024/03/19
